2026-05-17 16:37:08 | DEBUG | strands_evaluation.instrumentation.agent_plugins | Model response #7 [role=assistant block=1 tool_use] execute_ideal({"code": "# intent: Load roman_cities.csv and worldcities.csv and compute the number of modern cities with population >100000 within 0.1 degrees of any Roman city.\nimport pandas as pd\nimport numpy as np\n\n# load from s3\nroman_uri = 's3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-easy-3/files/roman_cities.csv'\nworld_uri = 's3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-hard-12/files/worldcities.csv'\n\nroman = pd.read_csv(roman_uri)\nworld = pd.read_csv(world_uri)\n\n# inspect columns\nprint('roman cols', roman.columns.tolist())\nprint('world cols', world.columns.tolist())\n\n# normalize roman lat/lon column names (note BOM in roman first column)\n# roman latitude column named 'Latitude (Y)' and longitude 'Longitude (X)'\nroman = roman.rename(columns={roman.columns[0]: roman.columns[0].strip()})\n\nroman_lat = 'Latitude (Y)'\nroman_lon = 'Longitude (X)'\n\nroman = roman[[roman_lat, roman_lon]].dropna()\nroman[roman_lat] = pd.to_numeric(roman[roman_lat], errors='coerce')\nroman[roman_lon] = pd.to_numeric(roman[roman_lon], errors='coerce')\nroman = roman.dropna()\n\n# prepare world cities\nworld['lat'] = pd.to_numeric(world['lat'], errors='coerce')\nworld['lng'] = pd.to_numeric(world['lng'], errors='coerce')\nworld['population'] = pd.to_numeric(world['population'], errors='coerce')\n\nworld_large = world[world['population']>100000].copy()\n\n# compute distance: for each world_large row, compute min distance to roman points\n# Use vectorized broadcasting in chunks to avoid memory blowup\nroman_coords = roman[[roman_lat, roman_lon]].to_numpy()\nworld_coords = world_large[['lat','lng']].to_numpy()\n\n# ensure order lat, lon matching roman lat, lon\n# roman has columns [Latitude (Y), Longitude (X)] so roman_coords[:,0]=lat\n\n# chunk over world cities\ndef min_distances(world_coords, roman_coords, chunk=5000):\n    mins = np.empty(world_coords.shape[0], dtype=float)\n    for i in range(0, world_coords.shape[0], chunk):\n        block = world_coords[i:i+chunk]\n        # compute squared distances\n        # (lat_diff)^2 + (lon_diff)^2\n        dlat = block[:,None,0] - roman_coords[None,:,0]\n        dlon = block[:,None,1] - roman_coords[None,:,1]\n        dist2 = dlat**2 + dlon**2\n        min2 = dist2.min(axis=1)\n        mins[i:i+chunk] = np.sqrt(min2)\n    return mins\n\nmins = min_distances(world_coords, roman_coords, chunk=2000)\n\n# count where mins <= 0.1\ncount = int((mins <= 0.1).sum())\nprint('count', count)\n\n# print count for submission\nprint(count)\n", "intent": "Compute number of modern cities (population>100k) within 0.1 degrees of any Roman city using Euclidean degrees distance.", "dataset_id": "kramabench-archeology-easy-3", "file_path": "files/roman_cities.csv"}) [toolUseId=call_VcmtDns1D6RrtcfIJGaQRGQw]
2026-05-17 16:37:08 | INFO | strands_evaluation.instrumentation.agent_plugins | Executing: execute_ideal({"code": "# intent: Load roman_cities.csv and worldcities.csv and compute the number of modern cities with population >100000 within 0.1 degrees of any Roman city.\nimport pandas as pd\nimport numpy as np\n\n# load from s3\nroman_uri = 's3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-easy-3/files/roman_cities.csv'\nworld_uri = 's3://sana-kramabench/datagov/kramabench-archeology-hard-12/files/worldcities.csv'\n\nroman = pd.read_csv(roman_uri)\nworld = pd.read_csv(world_uri)\n\n# inspect columns\nprint('roman cols', roman.columns.tolist())\nprint('world cols', world.columns.tolist())\n\n# normalize roman lat/lon column names (note BOM in roman first column)\n# roman latitude column named 'Latitude (Y)' and longitude 'Longitude (X)'\nroman = roman.rename(columns={roman.columns[0]: roman.columns[0].strip()})\n\nroman_lat = 'Latitude (Y)'\nroman_lon = 'Longitude (X)'\n\nroman = roman[[roman_lat, roman_lon]].dropna()\nroman[roman_lat] = pd.to_numeric(roman[roman_lat], errors='coerce')\nroman[roman_lon] = pd.to_numeric(roman[roman_lon], errors='coerce')\nroman = roman.dropna()\n\n# prepare world cities\nworld['lat'] = pd.to_numeric(world['lat'], errors='coerce')\nworld['lng'] = pd.to_numeric(world['lng'], errors='coerce')\nworld['population'] = pd.to_numeric(world['population'], errors='coerce')\n\nworld_large = world[world['population']>100000].copy()\n\n# compute distance: for each world_large row, compute min distance to roman points\n# Use vectorized broadcasting in chunks to avoid memory blowup\nroman_coords = roman[[roman_lat, roman_lon]].to_numpy()\nworld_coords = world_large[['lat','lng']].to_numpy()\n\n# ensure order lat, lon matching roman lat, lon\n# roman has columns [Latitude (Y), Longitude (X)] so roman_coords[:,0]=lat\n\n# chunk over world cities\ndef min_distances(world_coords, roman_coords, chunk=5000):\n    mins = np.empty(world_coords.shape[0], dtype=float)\n    for i in range(0, world_coords.shape[0], chunk):\n        block = world_coords[i:i+chunk]\n        # compute squared distances\n        # (lat_diff)^2 + (lon_diff)^2\n        dlat = block[:,None,0] - roman_coords[None,:,0]\n        dlon = block[:,None,1] - roman_coords[None,:,1]\n        dist2 = dlat**2 + dlon**2\n        min2 = dist2.min(axis=1)\n        mins[i:i+chunk] = np.sqrt(min2)\n    return mins\n\nmins = min_distances(world_coords, roman_coords, chunk=2000)\n\n# count where mins <= 0.1\ncount = int((mins <= 0.1).sum())\nprint('count', count)\n\n# print count for submission\nprint(count)\n", "intent": "Compute number of modern cities (population>100k) within 0.1 degrees of any Roman city using Euclidean degrees distance.", "dataset_id": "kramabench-archeology-easy-3", "file_path": "files/roman_cities.csv"})
